olarship and by the insights of cultural theory, Obstinate Hebrews is a fascinating tale of cultural appropriation cast in the light of modern society's preoccupation with the "other." Schechter argues that the French paid attention to the Jews because thinking about the Jews helped them reflect on general issues of the day. These included the role of tradition in religion, the perfectibility of human nature, national identity, and the nature of citizenship. In a conclusion comparing and contrasting the "Jewish question" in France with discourses about women, blacks, and Native Americans, Schechter provocatively widens his inquiry, calling for a more historically precise approach to these important questions of difference.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aFrench literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aJews in literature. 0aJewsxPublic opinion. 0aJewszFrancexIdentity. 0aJewszFrancexSocial conditionsy18th century. 0aPublic opinionzFrancexHistoryy18th century. 0aPublic opinionzFrancexHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  aacculturation.  aalienation.  aantisemitism.  aassimilation.  abelonging.  acitizenship.  acultural appropriation.  acultural theory.  adiscrimination.  aenlightenment.  aeurope.  aexile.  afeminism.  afrance.  afrench history.  afrench jews.  afrench revolution.  agender.  ahomeland.  ahuman nature.  aindigenous people.  aintolerance.  ajewish history.  ajewish population.  ajewish question.  ajudaica.  ajudaism.  anational identity.  anative americans.  anonfiction.  aothering.  apolitics.  aprejudice.  aracism.  areligion.  areligious difference.  asocial body.  asocial issues.  atradition.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Pre